04623nam a22006615i 9781531501556DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815315015567 a10.1515/97815315015562doi  a(DE-B1597)653138  a(OCoLC)1374245265  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL1050002bisacsh04a261.088/2819223//eng/20230404eng1 aRich, Bryce E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGender Essentialism and Orthodoxy :bBeyond Male and Female /cBryce E. Rich. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOrthodox Christianity and Contemporary Thought00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tPart I -- t1 Setting the Stage -- t2 (No) Male and Female Recapitulating Patristic Reflections on Gender -- t3 Gender Essentialism in Contemporary Orthodox Thought -- t4 Person, Gender, Sex, Sexuality -- tPart II -- t5 Women and the Priesthood -- t6 Homosexuality -- t7 Marriage The Sacrament of Love -- t8 Some Final Thoughts on Pastoral Care -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWithin contemporary orthodoxy, debates over sex and gender have become increasingly polemical over the past generation. Beginning with questions around women’s ordination, arguments have expanded to include feminism, sexual orientation, the sacrament of marriage, definitions of family, adoption of children, and care of transgender individuals. Preliminary responses to each of these topics are shaped by gender essentialism, the idea that male and female are ontologically fixed and incommensurate categories with different sets of characteristics and gifts for each sex. These categories, in turn, delineate gender roles in the family, the church, and society.Gender Essentialism and Orthodoxy offers an immanent critique of gender essentialism in the stream of the contemporary Orthodox Church influenced by the “Paris School” of Russian émigré theologians and their heirs. It uses an interdisciplinary approach to bring into conversation patristic reflections on sex and gender, personalist theological anthropology, insights from gender and queer theory, and modern biological understandings of human sexual differentiation. Though these are seemingly unrelated discourses, Gender Essentialism and Orthodoxy reveals unexpected points of convergence, as each line of thought eschews a strict gender binary in favor of more open-ended possibilities.The study concludes by drawing out some theological implications of the preceding findings as they relate to the ordination of women to the priesthood, same-sex unions and sacramental understandings of marriage, definitions of family, and pastoral care for intersex, transgender, and nonbinary parishioners.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGender identityxReligious aspectsxOrthodox Eastern Church. 0aSex rolexReligious aspectsxOrthodox Eastern Church. 4aGender & Sexuality. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Sexuality & Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aEssentialism.  aGender.  aLGBTQ.  aOrthodoxy.  aParis School.  aPatristics.  aPersonalism.  aSex.  aSexuality.  aTheological Anthropology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075167340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781531501556?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781531501556423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781531501556/original  a978-3-11-075167-3  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles